@node "Security_Codes" "Security Codes"

                             @{b}@{i} SECURITY CODES
                            STAR TREK ORIGINALS @{ub}@{ui}


 @{i}"Condition Green"@{ui} - In "@{"Bread and Circuses" link "TG_ORIG/BREAD_AND_CIRCUSES" 0}", Kirk says "Condition Green",
 which really was, "I am in trouble, but, do not interfere."

 Beam up safety code from "@{"Whom Gods Destroy" link "TG_ORIG/WHOM_GODS_DESTROY" 0}":
 Query: Spock - Queen to Queen's Level Three
 Response: Kirk - Queen to King's Level One

 Self-destruct code from "@{"Let That Be Your Last Battlefield" link "TG_ORIG/LET_THAT_BE_YOUR_LAST_BATTLEFIELD" 0}":
 Part 1: Kirk - 1-1A
 Part 2: Spock (Scotty) - 1-1A-2B
 Part 3: Scott (Chekov) - 1D-2D-3
 Part 4: Kirk - 0-0-0-Destruct-0 Initiate

 Abort: Kirk - 1-2-3-Continuity Abort Destruct Sequence

 @{b}(Name in parenthesis is who said it in Star Trek III: The Search for Spock)@{ub}
@endnode

@node "Shuttlecraft" "ShuttleCraft"

                 @{b}@{i}Shuttlecraft used in the Original Series@{ub}@{ui}

 The following are the shuttlecraft used on the original series:

 NCC-1701-2 - "Columbus"
 @{"The Galileo Seven" link "TG_ORIG/GALILEO_SEVEN" 0}

 NCC-1701-7 - "Galileo" (destroyed over Taurus II in
 @{"The Galileo Seven" link "TG_ORIG/GALILEO SEVEN" 0}

 NCC-1701-7 - "Galileo II"
 @{"This Way To Eden" link "TG_ORIG/THIS_WAY_TO_EDEN" 0}

 No available registry - "Copernicus"
 @{"The Galileo Seven" link "TG_ORIG/GALILEO_SEVEN" 0}

 Ironically, during the first season, for the episode "@{"The Enemy Within" link "TG_ORIG/THE_ENEMY_WITHIN" 0}", the
 production crew did not have the budget to construct a shuttlecraft.
@endnode

@node "Money" "Money"

                            @{b}@{i}MONEY IN THE FUTURE@{ub}@{ui}

 @{"Errand Of Mercy" link "TG_ORIG/ERRAND_OF_MERCY" 0} - Kirk tells Spock, "Starfleet has invested a great deal
 of money in our training. They're about due for a small return."

 @{"Operation - Annihilate" link "TG_ORIG/OPERATION_ANNIHILATE" 0} - Kirk says "I don't care what it takes or costs,
 just help him."

 @{"Mirror, Mirror" link "TG_ORIG/MIRROR,_MIRROR" 0} - "You want credits, Spock? I'll give 'em to you. You'll
 be a rich man." - Alternate Kirk

 @{"The Apple" link "TG_ORIG/THE_APPLE" 0} - Kirk says to Spock, "Do you know how much Starfleet has
 invested in you?" Spock starts to reply, "Twenty-two thousand, two hun . . ".
 Also, in this episode, Kirk says to Sulu, "You've earned your pay for the
 week."

 @{"The Doomsday Machine" link "TG_ORIG/THE_DOOMSDAY_MACHINE" 0} - "Scotty, you've earned your pay for the week." -
 Kirk

 @{"Catspaw" link "TG_ORIG/CATSPAW" 0} - "I'll bet credits to navy beans we can punch a hole in it." -
 Lt.  DeFalco.

 @{"The Trouble with Tribbles" link "TG_ORIG/THE_TROUBLE_WITH_TRIBBLES" 0} - There was some credit-bartering going on
 between Cyrano Jones and the bartender over the sale of several tribbles.
@endnode

@node "Religion" "Religion"

                          @{b}@{i}Religion In The Future@{ub}@{ui}

 The Cage/@{"The Menagerie" link "TG_ORIG/THE_MENAGERIE_PT.1" 0} - The keepers in the cage subject Pike to the
 hallucination that he is burning in Hell, complete with a lake of fire and
 brimstone. The Keeper refers to this as "a fable you once heard in childhood"
 Also, Vina compares herself and Pike to Adam and Eve.

 @{"The Man Trap" link "TG_ORIG/THE_MAN_TRAP" 0} - McCoy, just before he shoots Nancy Crater, says "Lord,
 forgive me."

 @{"Where No Man Has Gone Before" link "TG_ORIG/WHERE_NO_MAN_HAS_GONE_BEFORE" 0} - Gary Mitchell gets god-like powers, and
 creates a "Garden of Eden" on a desolate planet.

 @{"The Corbomite Maneuver" link "TG_ORIG/THE_CORBOMITE_MANEUVER" 0} - Balok states, "We make assumption you have a
 deity, or deities, or some such beliefs which comfort you."

 @{"Court Martial" link "TG_ORIG/COURT_MARTIAL" 0} - Cogley makes a reference to Moses (The Ten Commandments)
 as the basis of Federation law. Also, during Kirk's trial, he refers to the
 Bible as part of a long list of documents as part of the list referring to
 rights.

 @{"Return of the Archons" link "TG_ORIG/RETURN_OF_THE_ARCHONS" 0} - In reference to soulless creatures, Kirk
 comments to Spock, about Landru: "He may have been able to give (his computer)
 his knowledge, but he could not given it his knowledge, his wisdom, his soul,
 Mr.  Spock."

 @{"Errand of Mercy" link "TG_ORIG/ERRAND_OF_MERCY" 0} - Spocks says, "Even the gods did not spring into being
 overnight."

 @{"The City On The Edge of Forever" link "TG_ORIG/CITY_ON_THE_EDGE_OF_FOREVER" 0} - While the closing credits list a
 "Sister Edith Keeler", and while she does work at the "21st Street Mission",
 Edith Keeler probably isn't a nun. Many who work in such missions are referred
 to as "brothers" and "sisters". (For a cinematic example, see "Guys and
 Dolls")

 @{"Who Mourns For Adonais" link "TG_ORIG/WHO_MOURNS_FOR_ADONAIS" 0} - Apollo journeyed to Earth 5000 years ago from
 Pollux 4, and was worshipped along with the other gods by the populace. Chekov
 says, "Sorry, I've never met a god before." McCoy says, "Scotty doesn't
 believe in gods." Kirk also states, "Man has no need for gods. We find the One
 quite sufficient."

 @{"The Apple" link "TG_ORIG/THE_APPLE" 0} - Spock, Kirk, and McCoy make references to the biblical story
 of Genesis.

 @{"The Doomsday Machine" link "TG_ORIG/THE_DOOMSDAY_MACHINE" 0} - Matt Decker says, "They say there's no devil,
 Jim.  But there is. Straight out of Hell, I saw it...."

 @{"Catspaw" link "TG_ORIG/CATSPAW" 0} - Spock says to Kirk, "There are Earth legends of wizards and
 their familiars: demons in animal form, sent by Satan to serve the wizard."

 @{"I, Mudd" link "TG_ORIG/I,_MUDD" 0} - Harry Mudd makes reference to not surviving by bread alone, a
 direct reference, in part, to Jesus: "Man does not survive by bread alone, but
 by every word that proceedeth out of the mouth of God."

 @{"Journey to Babel" link "TG_ORIG/JOURNEY_TO_BABEL" 0} - The name of the planetoid Babel is lifted directly
 from the story of the Tower of Babel in Genesis 11.

 @{"Obsession" link "TG_ORIG/OBSESSION" 0} - Scotty says, "Thank heavens", to which Spock promptly
 replies, "Mr. Scott, there was no deity involved, it was my cross-circuiting
 to B that recovered them." McCoy then says, "Well, then, thank pitchforks and
 pointed ears. As long as it worked, Jim."

 @{"The Trouble With Tribbles" link "TG_ORIG/THE_TROUBLE_WITH_TRIBBLES" 0} - Korax said, "Kirk may be a swaggering,
 overbearing, tin-plated dictator with delusions of godhood, but he's not
 soft." Also, Spock paraphrases Matthew: "They remind me of the lilies of the
 field. They toil not, neither do they spin."

 @{"A Private Little War" link "TG_ORIG/A_PRIVATE_LITTLE_WAR" 0} - After Nona heals Kirk, she says "Our souls have
 been together."

 @{"Return to Tomorrow" link "TG_ORIG/RETURN_TO_TOMORROW" 0} - Sargon refers to Adam and Eve as possibly being
 travelers from their planet.

 @{"Patterns of Force" link "TG_ORIG/PATTERNS_OF_FORCE" 0} - Kirk, in reference to a helmet that Spock is
 wearing, says "That helmet covers a multitude of sins", a play on words of the
 apostle Peter: "Charity covereth the multitude of sins."

 @{"The Omega Glory" link "TG_ORIG/THE_OMEGA_GLORY" 0} - Capt. Tracey uses Spock's devilish appearance against
 him by likening him to "the servant of the Evil One" in the Yang's "Holy
 Book".

 @{"The Ultimate Computer" link "TG_ORIG/THE_ULTIMATE_COMPUTER" 0} - M5 says "Murder is contrary to the laws of God
 and man." Kirk adds, "Daystrom felt that such an act was an offense against
 the laws of God and man, and the computer that carried his engrams also
 believed it."

 @{"Bread and Circuses" link "TG_ORIG/BREAD_AND_CIRCUSES" 0} - McCoy says, "If you speak of worship of sorts, we
 represent many beliefs." Also, Uhura figures out that they aren't worshipping
 the sun, but the "Son of God". Also, Kirk specifically mentions, "Caesar and
 Christ, they had them both."

 @{"The Enterprise Incident" link "TG_ORIG/THE_ENTERPRISE_INCIDENT" 0} - Scott says to Kirk, "You look like the Devil
 himself."

 @{"The Paradise Syndrome" link "TG_ORIG/THE_PARADISE_SYNDROME" 0} - Kirk is thought to be a god by the Indian tribe
 when he emerges from the "temple".

 @{"Is There In Truth No Beauty" link "TG_ORIG/IS_THERE_IN_TRUTH_NO_BEAUTY" 0}- McCoy tells Spock, "You look like you paid
 a visit to the Devil himself."

 @{"Day of the Dove" link "TG_ORIG/DAY_OF_THE_DOVE" 0} - After Kirk says, "Go to the devil.", Kang replies, "We
 have no devil, Kirk, but we understand the habits of yours."

 @{"The Empath" link "TG_ORIG/THE_EMPATH" 0} - Ozaba quotes Psalm 95:4: "In his hand are the deep places
 of the Earth." At the end of the episode, Scotty quotes the parable of the
 Pearl of Great Price from Matthew.

 @{"Requiem for Methuselah" link "TG_ORIG/REQUIEM_FOR_METHUSELAH" 0} - Flint claimed that he was Methuselah, and that
 he knew Moses.

 @{"The Way To Eden" link "TG_ORIG/THE_WAY_TO_EDEN" 0} - Space hippies search for the mythical planet of Eden.

 Also, there are references to "purgatory", one by Spock in "This Side of
 Paradise", and one by Harry Mudd in "I, Mudd".
@endnode

